Object-Oriented Programming (OOP): Classes, objects, inheritance, and polymorphism.


Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in Python structures code using real-world concepts like classes and objects, promoting reusability and organization. The core principles are classes, objects, inheritance, and polymorphism, each demonstrated below with code examples
Classes and Objects
A class is a blueprint or template that defines the attributes (data) and methods (functions) that all objects of that class will have. An object is a specific instance of a class, with its own unique set of data for the defined attributes

# Define a class named 'Dog'
class Dog:
    # A class attribute, shared by all instances
    species = "Canis familiaris"

    # The __init__ method (constructor) initializes a new object
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name  # Instance attribute unique to each object
        self.age = age    # Instance attribute unique to each object

    # A method to perform an action
    def bark(self):
        return f"{self.name} says Woof!"

# Create objects (instances) of the Dog class
my_dog = Dog("Buddy", 3)
your_dog = Dog("Lucy", 5)

# Access attributes and call methods
print(f"{my_dog.name} is {my_dog.age} years old.")
print(your_dog.bark())


Inheritance
Inheritance allows a new class (child or derived class) to inherit attributes and methods from an existing class (parent or base class). This promotes code reuse and creates a hierarchical relationship between classes. The super() function is commonly used to call the parent class's methods or constructor

# Parent class
class Animal:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def eat(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is eating.")

# Child class inherits from Animal
class Dog(Animal):
    def __init__(self, name, breed):
        # Use super() to call the parent's __init__ method
        super().__init__(name)
        self.breed = breed

    # Add a new method specific to the child class
    def bark(self):
        print("Woof woof!")

# Create an object of the child class
my_dog = Dog("Buddy", "Golden Retriever")
my_dog.eat()   # Calls the inherited method from the parent
my_dog.bark()  # Calls the child's method


Polymorphism
Polymorphism (meaning "many forms") allows objects of different classes to be treated as objects of a common superclass, or to respond to the same method call in different ways. In Python, this is often achieved through method overriding, where a child class provides a specific implementation of a method that is already defined in its parent class.



class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        return "Animal makes a sound"

class Dog(Animal):
    # Override the speak method for Dog
    def speak(self):
        return "Woof!"

class Cat(Animal):
    # Override the speak method for Cat
    def speak(self):
        return "Meow!"

# A function that takes an Animal object (or any object with a 'speak' method)
def animal_sound(animal):
    print(animal.speak())

# Create different objects
dog_obj = Dog()
cat_obj = Cat()

# The same function call produces different results based on the object type
animal_sound(dog_obj)
animal_sound(cat_obj)
